# Data Science Lifecycle

- provides a structured framework for transforming raw information into actionable insights
- systematically navigating through each phrase to ensure that their analytical efforts are aligned with strategic objectives
	1. Identifying a Business Problem to Solve / Operationalizing a Business Objective
	2. Data Collection
	3. Data Cleaning and Preparation
	4. Exploratory Data Analysis and Feature Engineering
	5. Modeling
	6. Data Visualization
	7. Deployment and Monitoring
- Effective communication and visualization techniques help bridge technical findings with non-technical decision-makers, ensuring insights are understandable and impactful
- Serves as a roadmap for building robust, scalable solutions that drive innovation and create measurable value in dynamic business environments

# Identifying a Business Problem to Solve or Operationalizing a Business Objective

- Clearly defining the problem you aim to solve
- setting objectives
- identifying the key stakeholders
- determining the metrics that will measure success
- Clear, measurable objectives can significantly improve the likelihood of delivering actionable insights that drive tangible business impact
- Thoroughly understanding the problem scope ensures alignment among cross-functional teams and prevents misinterpretation of project goals
- A well-defined problem statement helps prioritize tasks and resources effectively

# Data Collection
- Gather relevant data
- recommended to consider context, timeframe, setting, and limitations to the data that can broaden or narrow the perspective of the information being curated
- When collecting and analyzing numerical data, we want to also consider
	- blending the findings with qualitative information and other data sources to strengthen your understanding and awareness of the setting /situation being researched
- Data can come from multiple sources
	- internal databases
	- external API's
	- third-party data providers
	- social media feeds
- Often need to navigate data governance policies and regulatory considerations when obtaining / sharing sensitive information
- establishing robust data ingestion pipelines helps maintain efficiency and reliability throughout the data lifecycle
- At this stage, it is crucial to ensure data quality (inaccurate or incomplete data can compromise downstream analysis)

# Data Cleaning and Preparation

- Ensures the dataset is accurate and consistent
- Transforming and standardizing variable sets the stage for more robust modeling
- need to proper handling of missing / outlier values can significantly enhance model performance and reduce the risk of bias
- Standardizing diverse data sources also facilitates easier integration with other systems and promotes reusability

# Exploratory Data Analysis(EDA) and Feature Engineering

- Exploratory Data Analysis(EDA) helps uncover patterns, relationships, and potential outliers
- Feature Engineering refines insights by creating new variables or modifying existing ones to boost predictive power
- Through EDA, data scientists can formulate hypothesis that guide further investigation and model selection
- Feature Engineering often requires
	- deep understanding of domain context
	- technical skills to translate observations into meaningful variables
- Effective EDA and Feature Engineering can dramatically reduce noise in the data, resulting in more reliable insights and cost-effective solutions.

# Modeling

- Wrap the Data, EDA, and Feature Engineering in an appropriate modeling technique
- involves hyperparameter tuning to optimize model accuracy and prevent overfitting
- essential to keep interpretability in mind, particularly in regulated industries where explainable models may be required
- Robust documentation ensures stakeholders understand the rationale behind the chosen approach and can effectively maintain or update the model over time

# Data Visualization

- enables stakeholder to easily interpret complex analyses through intuitive charts, graphs, and dashboards
- when designed effectively, visualizations help illuminate trends, highlight anomalies, and draw attention to key performance indicators, aiding in swift decision-making
- Robust visualization practices ensures insights are communicated clearly to non-technical audiences, increasing transparency and trust in data-driven solutions
- It is important to select the right visualization type since it can significantly enhance user engagement and comprehension of analytical findings

# Deployment and Monitoring

- Solution deployed into a production environment where it can deliver value
- Ongoing monitoring is critical to track model performance, detect data drift, and retrain or adjust the model as conditions change
- Effective deployment strategies incorporate continuous integration and continuous delivery (CI/CD) pipelines for seamless updates
- Organizations gain benefit from implementing clear performance metrics and alerting mechanisms that highlight unusual trends or drops in accuracy
- By fostering a culture of continuous improvement, businesses can extend the value of data-driven solutions and remain competitive in dynamic markets
